<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06261036 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06261036 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  HEALTH; ELDERLY; HEART; DRUG; BLACKS; SMOKING; STATISTIC; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  LESS than half the elderly people who are at moderate risk of developingflu-related pneumonia get a flu shot, even though many deaths could beprevented each winter if these people were immunized, say Harvard Universityresearchers.;   Elderly people who are frail and ill are at increased risk ofdeveloping pneumonia and other flu-related complications, reported Dr. MurielR. Gillick. But even elderly people who are in good health are at risk duringthe flu season.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Science andamp; Medicine  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  MANY AT-RISK ELDERLY NOT IMMUNIZED FOR FLU  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Briefs; Science Scene  </MEMO><TEXT>     Flu vaccines are given in the fall to protect against illness during thewinter. The vaccine is 50 percent to 80 percent effective.; DRUG BEING PULLED;  A heart drug linked to higher death rates among patients being treated formild irregular heartbeats will be withdrawn from the market, its maker saidMonday.;   Encainide hydrochloride, or Enkaid, won't be withdrawn until Dec.16, allowing doctors to find substitutes, said a spokesman for BristolLaboratories. He warned patients not to stop using the drug without consultingtheir doctors.; BLACKS, SMOKING;   During much of the nearly 30-year waragainst smoking, public-health groups have placed special emphasis on youngblacks, who they have thought are likeliest to begin smoking in childhood.;  But in the first comprehensive study of smoking by high school students, theCenters for Disease Control discovered this belief might be unfounded.;  White high schoolers, the CDC found, are seven times more likely to be regularsmokers than their black counterparts. The survey of 11,631 high schoolstudents in all 50 states found that 15.9 percent of white students and 7.4percent of Hispanic students smoked every day, compared to 2.3 percent ofblack students.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Compiled by Sylvia Wright from Mercury News wire services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910917  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  September  </MONTH><PG.COL>  2E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  276  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday, September 17, 199100261036,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>